A Chinese New Year dinner in 2015 turned out to be life-changing for Mrs Germaine Littlewood.

Then 37 years old, she found out from her father that she was adopted. He gave her his blessings to find her birth mother. 

Mrs Littlewood tried to track down her mother through the convent where she was given up for adoption and even took a DNA test to learn more about her ancestry. With help from the Crime Library, she and her mother finally celebrated their first CNY reunion this year.
Full story in bio @straits_times 
üì∏: Alphonsus Chern

Who else is ready to be a DJ with the viral lohei app this CNY? üòâ

The DJ Beng lohei app allows users to tap their smartphone screens to play recordings of traditional auspicious exclamations that accompany the tossing of yusheng - as such shouting has been banned in Singapore due to the risk of spreading Covid-19.

"This app is popular only because of the regulations. So long as it's needed, I'll add more features but, eventually, hopefully, we won't need to use it any more," says Mr Koh Beng Liang, the developer behind the free Web-based app.

Despite the app's meteoric rise in popularity, Mr Koh has no intention of monetising it.

Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Yong Li Xuan

The DJ Beng lohei app allows users to tap their smartphone screens to play recordings of traditional auspicious exclamations that accompany the tossing of yusheng - as such shouting has been banned in Singapore due to the risk of spreading Covid-19.

"This app is popular only because of the regulations. So long as it's needed, I'll add more features but, eventually, hopefully, we won't need to use it any more," says Mr Koh Beng Liang, the developer behind the free Web-based app.

Despite the app's meteoric rise in popularity, Mr Koh has no intention of monetising it.

description:
üèò The kampung spirit is strong at Block 117 Tampines Street 11.

Mr Abdullah Abdul Rahman Abdullah, who lives on the 4th floor of the HDB block, has put up Chinese New Year decorations to thank his neighbours for supporting his family following his 83-year-old father's death last December.

Mr Abdullah even placed 2 chairs outside his home for those who want to admire the flowers along the corridor.

The 36-year-old and his brother also bought boxes of oranges to distribute to their neighbours, and prepared special red packets for the children of shop owners who helped them with the decorations.

A retired resident of the block said the decorations bring cheer to people like her, especially after a hard year.

description:
Update: Singapore and Hong Kong have decided to defer the start of the air travel bubble to beyond this month given that the number of local unlinked cases in Hong Kong is still high, says CAAS.
The exact start date of the arrangement will be reviewed late this month.
The move comes as Hong Kong hunkers down under harsher social distancing measures in anticipation of what health authorities have warned could be the worst Covid-19 wave so far.
Hong Kong's daily new infections have crossed 70 for more than a week.
The spike was led initially by a growing dance club cluster of more than 500, most of whom are tai tais and their young dancing instructors.
Link in bio @straits_times
#travelbubble #hongkong #singapore #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

comments: As 1 country it is easy to say what needs to get done and everyone toe the line. This takes some leadership foresight and a public who's generally willing to cooperate. Opening up a country to another? Unless both countries have the common same detection, tracing, control methods and direction (just like 1 country) setting measurements to determine when to pull the plug is not enough. Are the countries in a travel bubble willing to adapt and adjust to each other for a common way forward- just like a single country's response, containment and treatment methods? Are the people of both countries trusting enough of the other? If not, then travel bubbles anywhere would be some way off.

üåé No matter where you are in the world, the word "lockdown" has likely affected you one way or another.
Lexicographers said they picked the word because it had become synonymous with the experience of populations across the world as governments look to curb the Covid-19 pandemic.
Collins registered more than a quarter of a million usages of "lockdown" during 2020, against only 4,000 the previous year.
Other words included in the longer list of 10 words of the year include "coronavirus", "social distancing", "self-isolate", "key worker" and "furlough".

comments: If pray in the MRT train or Supermarket can have more congregants!!!
description:
Prayers at mosques in Singapore for Hari Raya Haji were quieter this year due to safe distancing measures to curb the spread of Covid-19.
The usual prayer assembly at Masjid Sultan used to attract at least 5,000 worshippers, but this year it was split into 2 sessions of just 50 people each.
Most mosques held 3 sessions with no more than 50 worshippers - who had to book slots online - each time.
The Straits Times would like to wish all our readers Selamat Hari Raya Haji. Stay safe!
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Shintaro Tay
#selamathariraya #SGUnited #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

üè∏ CCA experiences and school activities are "important elements of our students' holistic development", said MOE.
Some safe management measures that will be put in place following the CCA resumption include:
üîπ Maximum of 20 students per activity
üîπ Modified game rules will apply, such as students having to remain at least 1m apart
üîπ Schools will continue to screen all visitors, including coaches and instructors, for flu-like symptoms
CCAs and school activities that will remain suspended include those that involve high levels of body contact, such as taekwondo sparring or rugby scrums; or high exposure to aerosol and splatters, such as the playing of wind instruments or singing in a choir.
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Ong Wee Jin
#coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

Robots can observe safe distancing too!

Called Spot, the robot will be broadcasting a recorded message reminding park visitors to observe safe distancing measures.
Don't worry about bumping into Spot as it is fitted with safety sensors to detect objects and people within 1m to avoid collision.
Robots can observe safe distancing too!
üé•: Gin Tay
#cybark #robot #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes #SGUnited #StayHome #circuitbreaker

Called Spot, the robot will be broadcasting a recorded message reminding park visitors to observe safe distancing measures.
Don't worry about bumping into Spot as it is fitted with safety sensors to detect objects and people within 1m to avoid collision.
Robots can observe safe distancing too!
üé•: Gin Tay
#cybark #robot #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes #SGUnited #StayHome #circuitbreaker

What has 4 wheels and never tires of reminding people to practise safe distancing at parks?
If you guessed the O-R3 autonomous robot, you're a psychic!
PUB's latest "safe distancing ambassador" conducts daily patrols in the mornings and evenings at Bedok Reservoir, when human traffic at the park is the highest.
It is also armed with sensors that can capture, record and process data that can be sent to officers in real time.
Similar robots will be deployed at Pandan and MacRitchie Reservoirs.
Don't be alarmed if you see the O-R3 rumbling around!
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Jason Quah
#autonomousrobot #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes #SGUnited #StayHome #circuitbreaker

What has 4 wheels and never tires of reminding people to practise safe distancing at parks?
If you guessed the O-R3 autonomous robot, you're a psychic!
PUB's latest "safe distancing ambassador" conducts daily patrols in the mornings and evenings at Bedok Reservoir, when human traffic at the park is the highest.
It is also armed with sensors that can capture, record and process data that can be sent to officers in real time.
Similar robots will be deployed at Pandan and MacRitchie Reservoirs.
Don't be alarmed if you see the O-R3 rumbling around!

description:
Concerned about safe distancing issues at the supermarket? What if the supermarket came to you?
Starting today, residents living in 5 mature estates can buy their groceries from NTUC FairPrice vans parked near their homes.
The pilot initiative, dubbed FairPrice on Wheels, chose locations which have more than 30% of residents who are above 60 years old and living in 3-room Housing Board flats.
Details of the vans' locations in the link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Jason Quah, Lim Yaohui

comments: Guys please be reasonable. The government is quickly adapting approaches based on the situation! Things have changed alot in 6 weeks. They know masks helps, but 6 weeks ago, number of healthy people is higher, probability of spread is low, but irrational fear (selfishness, panic hoarding) was high so that was the recommended approach. But today, there's a higher spread in community over time, but higher trust in government to act (e.g. society observed how they quickly planning resources and manpower to create and give out hand sanitizers and now reusable masks), so the approach changed. It's about adapting quickly based on factors e.g. society, resources needed, time available, probability of virus spread. Not about staunchly sticking to 1 way just because you don't want people to criticise.

Here are the stricter safe distancing measures that will be introduced to stem the spread of the coronavirus in Singapore:
1. All events and gatherings with 250 or more participants to be suspended until June 30
2. Suspension of all social activities for seniors by government agencies will be extended for another 2 weeks until April 7
3. Operators of venues accessible to the public, such as restaurants and cinemas, are required to ensure separation of at least 1m between patrons
4. Employers strongly advised to allow their employees to work from home, or implement staggered working hours where telecommuting is not possible
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Ng Sor Luan

2. Suspension of all social activities for seniors by government agencies will be extended for another 2 weeks until April 7
3. Operators of venues accessible to the public, such as restaurants and cinemas, are required to ensure separation of at least 1m between patrons
4. Employers strongly advised to allow their employees to work from home, or implement staggered working hours where telecommuting is not possible

Singapore is taking strong steps to stop the coronavirus from spreading within the country, using social distancing as a major line of defence.
This is on top of tougher measures to prevent infections being imported from elsewhere.
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Alphonsus Chern
#coronavirus #covid19 #socialdistancing #StraitsTimes

Using a new test that is able to detect infections even in recovered patients, contact tracers from the Ministry of Health and the police were able to track the infection to 2 travellers from Wuhan, who were cases 8 and 9.
The Wuhan couple were linked to the Life Church and Missions cluster, a Chinese New Year family gathering at Mei Hwan Drive, and finally to the Grace Assembly of God which to date is linked to 23 cases.
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Ng Sor Luan

comments: Ben, please get in touch with Mental Health, Anxiety Disorder before it's too late. You need to take psychotic medications prescribed by a psychiatrist doctor. Staying indoors won't help you. You must be brave and fight against all odds. I'm not saying it's easy but once you have take the first steps and seek help you will see light at the end of the tunnel. I'm saying this because I'm helping a friend who's going through exactly you are going through now. The progress and outcome is so much brighter than before he had the treatment. There's no magic pill remember this!
